    {
      "id": "6c7388559ce349d5d564e02e6ee8f6e965f7138e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-19 08:54:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c0d97c3ba04fa00e8ec809f88edc63fa5b8f4109",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-19 09:17:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(6 inline comments)\n\nExcept technical issues noted inline, I doubt in general approach itself. I really dislike the idea of changing llog internals for just single case in one of the llog users - changelog. IMHO, we need to estimate at first how to make it atomic in changelog code itself using current llog mechanisms.\nE.g. shouldn't changelog itself care about atomic changes here using some locking or writting extended changelog_record. Would it difficult to update changelog tools to be aware of such extended record?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2e52f95964f3ecb3b5a35f86c00a81e6c080ab6e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-19 13:08:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (7 inline comments)\n\nThe background is that Catalog has used loghandl->lgh_lock to serialize write operation, if it can write multiple records, then these records can be consecutive. But Catalog and llog use the same set of interface struct llog_operations, if I want to allow Catalog write multiple records, all implementations of llog_operations have to change their interface though they only write one record each time.\n\nIf we don't take advantage of Catalog serialization mechanism, we can add another lock to serialize all changelog write, but currently there is not a set of interfaces for changelog, but uses llog APIs all around, then all the places changelog write should be lock protected. Firstly this lock is redundant, besides, it may hurt parallel performance.\n\nI don't find an easy way to solve this in user space utility, because several rename records can be written without orders, then there is no way to find matched RNMTO for RNMFRM record.\n\nMike, I don't object to other ways to fix this, since you're  expert on this, please give some advice.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "8fcced0939af21aa94c733646112ecd65497df71",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-04-19 13:20:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 5.8/x86_64, CentOS release 6.2/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/2cfa6ebc-8a22-11e1-bd58-525400d2bfa6).  Ran 5 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "55f6dca006a95184087e12850865b62ab2925d72",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-19 15:03:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (4 inline comments)\n\nI see why it is needed. Maybe I am too late saying that but why changelog has 2 recs for rename at all? Just because all data doesn't fit into changelog_rec for rename or there was demand for that? I don't see big problem in having bigger record for rename operation, changelog processing code needs just be aware about that.\n\nIf that is too late to change then I am thinking about rw locking in changelog itself, all changelog updates go though changelog_ns_store() and changelog_data_store() so we can have all locking inside. It is write lock for rename update and read lock for others, so concurrency will not be affected. And we can keep your idea about _prep() for rename updates and single call to update itself.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7d7a4bb2c8d74f2081be5618e0905fb6ac6cb594",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-20 05:27:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)\n\nI suppose the purpose of using two records for rename is to saving space? since all other operations need only one fid, but I don't think that's a good idea.\n\nGiven that we've already have two records for rename, and changing the changelog format could break user applications, I'm fine with changing lustre internal code to make rename records consecutive.\n\nThis patch looks fine with me, expect the defects that Mike has pointed out.\n\nHi, Mike, do you concern about that porting this to orion will be little difficult? I personally think it looks cleaner than adding anohter dedicated lock for changelog, and it could probably be used for other features later.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0301440e1085d5fb26cfd73671abdb6910e62016",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-20 06:05:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWell, partially. I am concerned about changing llog API and internals in general, such things should have good reasons and in this particular case it is not so, nobody will use this except changelog in case of rename. But llog code will have that always for all callers even when changelog is turned off. It is not about overhead, we can you unlikely() for condition checks but core code become more complex and hard to follow for nothing. Also I don't like any cases when Lustre is chaged in favor of tools, I believe it should be backward, especially when we are talking about core functions and API.\n\nI would prefer isolated solution in changelog itself because it will affect only changelog code and work only when changelog is turned on. Using rwlock is not more complex then multiple records changes and placed in mdd changelog code only. The only one issue with that is possible contention on renames.  So ideal solution would be single extended record for rename, can we discuss with community that a little? Maybe everybody is unhappy about having 2 records for rename and it is OK to change that?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3773c96e4a0ac0cd60a85c8298472ab14eae8ab0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 185
      },
      "date": "2012-04-20 08:53:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI think there is no practical interest in having 2 differents records for a single atomic operation like rename, and I guess this record has been splitted for Lustre internal implementation reasons.\nFor now, client apps have to manage the rename peer a specific way, and for sure it would be better to handle rename like every other record.\nI would not be shocked by an API (liblustreapi) change for that, as long as there is a way to detect it from a configure.ac script\n(eg. by testing existance of a call, a structure, a field in a structure, ...)\nThomas",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
